class Solution {
    public int minimumScore(String s, String t) {
        int result = 0;
        int n = s.length();
        int m = t.length();

        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            for (int j = 0; j < m; j++) {
                if (s.charAt(i) == t.charAt(j)) {
                    result = Math.max(result, j + 1);
                }
            }
        }
        return result;
    }
}
```

efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(n * m)
space complexity: O(1)
energy implications: LOW

Explanation:

We iterate through the characters of string s and t using nested loops. For each character in s, we check if it matches any character in t. If a match is found, we update the result variable with the index of the matching character plus one. This ensures that we keep track of the indices of the characters that are part of the subsequence formed by removing characters from t. Finally, we return the minimum score achieved.

The time complexity is O(n * m) because we iterate over both strings s and t. The space complexity is O(1) as we only use a constant amount of space for the result variable. The energy implications are low as the solution only requires a small amount of energy consumption.

